From the personal journal of Dr. J. H. Carter.

Press any key to continue.
March 2nd, 1933 - The ship sailed today. Just twelve hours ago, upon setting foot on dry land for the first time in four months, I had entertained the thought of never again subjecting myself to the rolling monotony of sea life. But as the rusted freighter ‘SS Fawcett’ finally vanished over the horizon I must admit that I felt a sudden urge to steal one of the local fisherman’s canoes and give chase, thus abandoning what has been my life’s work.

Press any key to continue.
I proceeded in haste to the residence of Professor X. Position, the preeminent academic expert on the Island of Ankrum and its inhabitants. After knocking five times, I received a warm greeting followed by a warm meal and a wealth of information that should prove invaluable in reaching my goal.

Press any key to continue.
It was through the Professor (who prefers to be addressed as ‘PP’) that I was able to secure a group of the finest village warriors as escort on my jungle expedition. The young Chieftain (he cannot be older than twenty-one), having never ventured beyond the base of the mountain, has declared that he will personally accompany me to the summit. It is there I hope to, at long last, determine the truth behind the legend of the Serpent’s Eye.

Press any key to continue.
Should I fail to return, I have left explicit instructions for this journal to be mailed to my assistant in the archeological department of Schoedsack University as both proof of this expedition and a warning: In the likely event of my disappearance, there will be no attempt made at a rescue, for I fear that, should anyone follow in my footsteps...

Type CLOSE JOURNAL.
